You ever think about how if the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event had gone a little differently, say allowing some bipedal dinosaurs to eek out an existence in North America? I don't think you truly grasp just how long 65 million years is. Let's be generous for the sake of discussion and use 70 thousand years as a measuring stick and do a quick division. By a factor of 928.57, raptors would have been roaming the Earth longer than modern Man has existed in any form. Use 45 thousand years and it's a factor of 1444.44.

Even if we go back 7 million years to when humans were barely distinguishable from a bonobo, and it's a factor of 9.29. Just call it 100, 1500 and 10 respectively for quick discussion.

What I'm saying here is, nothing like humans would have ever evolved with anything like a raptor survival event in this planet's ecological history. It's not just a single species of raptors you'd have to account for. It's an entire ecology of pre-mammal creatures that never would have let mammals gain the foothold they did 63 million years ago in the wake of the KT extinction.

If you wanted to go down this path, you're going to have to do a lot more evolutionary gymnastics than a Star Trek episode that was embarrassing in every one of its fundamental premises.

https://memory-alpha.fandom.com/wiki/Distant_Origin_(episode)
search string "star trek voyager hadrosaur"

But, if you want to really go down that path and really go through the work it would take to make it less than laughable even as a fifth (or third) grade "science" fiction story, I gift you now the working title: Survival Event. You're welcome.

Also suggest searching "shy stegosaurus of cricket creek" for some entertaining research, originally written in 1955 for first & second grade level children. It's copyright free and available for download with at least one sequel that I know of.

nta, but hello Mr. Disingenious
If you want more stories that meet your specifications
1: provide a per-species/genus list of minimums.
2: write stories according to those specs
3: shift the attitudes here with a result that has stronger characters than our currently best stories

One of the fun parts I have on both sides of beta reading is what went into a character and what/how it foreshadows. At times, this goes against whatever headcanon you might have because my primary sources are
1: myth/legend
2: a few generalized facts that I can either play to or against
3: classic stories, so for foxes I'd reference Renard in some manner
4: whatever videos I can find that let me sketch how the character moves/postures in my head

So let's take a very familiar species - the cheetah
Very fast, and while a capable predator it's also not a realistic threat to an adult human. They're very slender compared to most felids and captive cubs are often paired with puppies to reduce their anxiety.
If I played to much of that, I might pick a track & field setting. She throws herself into training because she remembers elementary school and the girls that bullied her. And then a competitor from a rival team catches her eye, but he starts talking to her like she was some lioness.
If I played against some of the traits, she's long since worked off most of her anxiety through the help of her long-suffering childhood canid BFF. The canid wants her to meet the friend of her BF, and hijinks ensue.

tl;dr: you're not paying me or working with me as a co-writer

>>44614789
>Is it necessary to make it more about the the fact that she's a canine or is it enough to have sprinkled in elements like the example above through the whole story?
These are not necessarily connected elements.

>make it more about the the fact that she's a [ _______ ]
>insert whatever species
Why is this species in the story? What about this species fits into your world building? Would the story change at all if she was a bird? In what way(s)? If you were writing about an only-human world, would your white European male be married to/dating a black woman who immigrated from Africa? Would it change anything about the story? How?

That "How" indicates the "how much more about the fact that" part of your question. Take a deep dive into your own head when you decide to use a man made domestic breed that has been cultivated for aesthetic and purpose. Ask yourself "What the fuck are you doing, nigger?" Seriously, what the living fuck is a French poodle or a greyhound doing as a "species" in any universe? And how the fuck did it get there?

>sprinkle in elements
This is the topic of story pacing. You reveal what you need to reveal when it is necessary to enlighten the reader on world building and plot points. As the author, you make these decisions, then you get crucified or applauded for your sense of pacing and skill as a storyteller. Does your story require a half chapter of exposition to set the stage? Do it. Do it right and well for what your story requires.

Does your story benefit from a slow burn, revealing mystery after mystery that leads the reader down a path of imagination that builds immersion in their headspace? Then do it that way. Following a trail of implied breadcrumbs can force or lead a reader into immersion. How you lay those tasty breadcrumbs out, whether you tempt or bully your reader ... those are the artistic nuances you need to develop as a writer.

>this story really has almost zero amount of world-building. It's a contemporary office setting,
There's nothing really wrong with that. If it's an office setting with different species, you can treat it more like Zootopia and just have fun with it, focus on some of the silly differences.

>first time I'll do creative writing just for fun
Jesus, man. Focus on having fun. Learn the lessons in good faith and with a thick skin, apply them to the next piece. If you're not having fun doing it, it's going to become torture. Don't let yourself get into a negative feedback loop like that, especially at the very beginning. Creative writing is a marathon. Pace yourself and train for the long game.

You've probably heard that a writer has to learn to love their characters enough to be able to kill them off when necessary? A similar thing applies to some individual works and ideas. Do what you've got to do, what you can do. And let it go that they aren't perfect. Very much especially the first works will be flawed. Let it go and move on, don't let concern for possible flaws prevent you from finishing a project and moving to the next.

If it's a truly genius idea, you can rewrite it in ten years the way it should have been. Consider this a draft or a placeholder that establishes your claim on this particular story. It's notes for how young and enthusiastic you were when you first conceptualized it, notes that will let you revisit it later, after you've learned from far more spectacular failures yet to come.

Cheer up. Today isn't your worst day ever. It's you're worst day ever .... so far.

I don't understand what provoked this question; I deliberately omitted a clear reference to extant birds. Fwiw, they've a rich existence in this setting, albeit one that's not narratively prognostic or very present at face. I've always been on the fence about beakier ornithoids in settings with anthro raptors. I like to assume some evolutionary back-and-forth of traits (like beaks) between euraptorid ancestors and modern latenids (anthro raptors) anyway. But I'm always open to being persuaded either way.
An aside, but this setting has beaked variants of primitive ornithoids that are parallel to monkeys. I'm unsure if I'll ever have much reason to exposit details like that in-story, but I'll probably sketch them eventually.
